  "text": "Grafana's database migration framework is implemented in the `pkg/services/sqlstore/migrator/` package and consists of several key components:\n\n**Migration Runner (migrator.go:35-436)**: The `Migrator` struct serves as the core migration executor. It manages a list of migrations, maintains a `migration_log` table (type `MigrationLog` at migrator.go:49-56) to track executed migrations by ID, SQL statement, success status, errors, and timestamp. Key methods include:\n- `RunMigrations()` (lines 191-231): Orchestrates the migration process with database locking support\n- `doMigration()` (lines 305-362): Executes individual migrations within transactions\n- `InTransaction()` (lines 415-436): Provides transactional safety with automatic rollback on errors\n- `GetMigrationLog()` (lines 162-178): Retrieves previously executed migrations from the log table\n\nThe migration runner creates and manages the `migration_log` table automatically via `AddCreateMigration()` (lines 123-135), which defines the table schema with migration_id, sql, success, error, and timestamp columns.\n\n**SQL Dialect Abstraction (dialect.go:19-486)**: The `Dialect` interface (lines 19-108) provides database-agnostic SQL generation. It's implemented by three dialect classes:\n- `BaseDialect` (lines 135-486): Contains shared implementation for common SQL operations\n- `MySQLDialect` (mysql_dialect.go:16-320): MySQL-specific implementation with GET_LOCK/RELEASE_LOCK for locking\n- `PostgresDialect` (postgres_dialect.go:15-362): PostgreSQL-specific implementation with pg_try_advisory_lock/pg_advisory_unlock\n- `SQLite3` (sqlite_dialect.go:11-222): SQLite-specific implementation\n\nEach dialect handles database-specific syntax for:\n- Quoting identifiers\n- Type mapping (DB_Bool, DB_Int, DB_Varchar, etc. defined in types.go:74-119)\n- Index operations\n- Column checks\n- Upsert statements\n- Table locks and unlocks\n\n**Migration Types (types.go:17-31, migrations.go:1-200)**: The framework supports multiple migration patterns:\n- `Migration` interface (types.go:17-26): Base interface requiring SQL() and condition checking\n- `CodeMigration` interface (types.go:28-31): Supports programmatic migrations with Exec() method\n- `RawSQLMigration` (migrations.go:28-86): For dialect-specific SQL with fallback support\n- `AddColumnMigration` (migrations.go:88-112): Adds columns with automatic condition checking\n- `AddIndexMigration` (migrations.go:146-165): Creates indexes with existence conditions\n- `AddTableMigration` (migrations.go:186+): Creates new tables\n- `RenameColumnMigration`, `DropIndexMigration`: Additional structural changes\n\n**Migration Conditions (conditions.go:1-49)**: Conditions prevent re-execution of migrations:\n- `MigrationCondition` interface (lines 3-6)\n- `ExistsMigrationCondition`, `NotExistsMigrationCondition`: Check query results\n- `IfIndexExistsCondition`, `IfIndexNotExistsCondition`: Index-specific checks\n- `IfColumnNotExistsCondition`: Column existence checks\n\n**Rollback Handling**: The framework implements rollback via `InTransaction()` (migrator.go:415-436) and `doMigration()` (migrator.go:321-354), which wraps each migration in a database transaction. On error, the transaction automatically rolls back via `sess.Rollback()` (line 424), and failed migrations are logged in the migration_log table (lines 343-346) before the transaction is rolled back.\n\n**Migration Registration (migrations.go)**: The `OSSMigrations` struct coordinates all framework migrations, calling `AddMigration()` for each migration type in order. This is the entry point where all specific migrations (user, dashboard, datasource, alert migrations, etc.) are registered with the migrator.\n\nThe framework supports executing multiple migrations in sequence, with each migration:\n1. Checking if already executed via migration_log\n2. Evaluating its condition to skip if already applied\n3. Executing SQL or code within a transaction\n4. Recording success/failure in migration_log\n5. Rolling back automatically on error"
}

